metadata.name: Gkrint #25
metadata.description:
Gkrint is a celebration of minimalism, colour, and space using the humble grid, a foundation of generative art, and movement. Through this collaboration, Ballzerino and George explore the relationships between these elements.

Inspired by the timeless principles of Bauhaus design, Ballzerino carefully curated custom colour palettes and selected geometric shapes, while George encoded the creative process into an algorithm, bringing the compositions to life, and putting the CPU to work finding new and unexpected compositions within our framework.

Gkrint is Ballzerino's genesis generative art drop.

Controls:
SPACE - pause / resume
click (or tap) - change colour selection (within same palette)
hold 'f' - speed up animation

Tested on Windows / Mac / iOS / Android. Chrome recommended for the best experience.

metadata.name: Concrete #261
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: QuadTubes - Abstract Variations #105
metadata.description:
This piece features abstract patterns created using an algorithm I call QuadTubes.

It works by continuously stroking a set of quadratic curves that run through a set of points while rotating those points along a constant orbit.

This piece features 13 different arrangements and 11 different colors sets, so there should be around 20 pieces of each arrangement. Check the variations function to preview the different arrangements and styles.

The piece will slowly render and automatically pause after reaching its final form. You can press Space to Pause/Unpause the piece and let it run longer resulting in more saturated colors.

You can adjust the rendering speed with up/down-arrows or you can also load the page with
'&Speed=*'
at the end of the url to adjust the rendering speed (default = 25) and press S at any time to save an image of any state of the animation.
 
Initial minters will receive 10% royalties.


PLEASE NOTE: 
This piece was developed in and is best viewed in Chrome (100.0.4896.127). Moreover hardware acceleration needs to be enabled in the browser settings. There are still some browsers & devices that struggle with this piece, most notably iOS and Firefox. There is a fallback which is enabled in Firefox and iOS by default that works without hardware acceleration but produces notably different results in texture and color saturation (especially on iOS). You may force the fallback by appending "&noHA=true" to the url in live view and force the original rendering by appending "&forceHA=true" (Note you can combine multiple URL parameters with an "&", eg "www.fxhash.xyz[...]?Speed=50&forceHA=true").
 Please make sure that you have a device and browser capable of rendering this piece before minting.

metadata.name: Quantum Places Lost in Time #177
metadata.description:
A frozen scene from a lost dimension
An alternative of where we once were, or where we will be 
Caught in the moment and set in place
Between all states
Static pixels on a digital canvas

The path to this collection has created many alternatives lost in time themselves. It began as a study of points of light, with geometric objects in the background. The background objects developed a life of their own and then birds, and ships, made out of bezier shapes became the focal points. Then everything got lost in clouds before the collection as it stands now emerged. Aside from the published traits, many of the artifacts created on the way are still generated. For example, star fields, birds, sonars and gas bubbles. These are sometimes visible, but when they appear, it is simply by some chaotic chance.

This collection has been coded with P5js and WebGL. Half of all primary sales proceeds, and secondary royalties, are assigned to the Processing Foundation.

Press s to download a 2880 x 3840 jpeg

metadata.name: Continuum #238
metadata.description:
This project is the culmination of many generative art experiments I have run throughout 2022. It relies heavily on the random walks through color and space techniques I have been working with, but also introduces other elements related to 2D and 3D rotation, framing and grains.

Continuum began as an abstract composition made up of a set of interacting elements against a background. This is still true. However, in my own mind, I have come to consider many Continuum pieces as peculiar, stylized observations of massive futuristic spacial, or quantum, constructions. Maybe even involving a wormhole through the fabric of space-time for some civilization well past 1 on the Kardashev scale. At the center is an erratic crystalline form, which is fed by power trains, and all around is a massive multicolored rotating containment structure.

Aside from the standard, inverse, threshold and washed types, the most defining trait of each composition is the “Back Style” which relates to a point of construction, activity or deconstruction of these structures. This is further refined by the panel style, the panel density and the rotation level. The other traits largely relate to color variability and aesthetics. 

This work has been coded using p5.js, and half of all royalties from the primary, and secondary, sales are assigned to the processing foundation.

Press s to download a 2400x2400 pixel image.

This work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License.

metadata.name: The String #359
metadata.description:
|| Anniversary project for FX(hash) 1st birthday ||

Each virtual object consists of 365 lights.
Each light represents one day of the year.

We go through every single day, thinking it's all crucial. Yet, from a perspective, it all gets compressed into a single thread. Some of the events are brighter and more memorable. Others just blend or fade away.

I welcomed November 2021 with huge excitement and celebration. The joyful beginning of the month was followed by weeks of misery, anxiety, denial, and acceptance. It was a hard time, but in the long run, it was liberating and started a process of change. Change that happens dynamically to this day.

I couldn't join you last year, but I'm celebrating with you today!



In memory of my Dad.



Donations:
40% – Savepakistan - Flood Relief Fundraiser
10% – Three.js
